1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,240
For 2 years, the entire AI industry

2
00:00:02,760 --> 00:00:07,120
agreed on how to give a model memory.

3
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:09,600
You chopped your documents into

4
00:00:07,120 --> 00:00:12,000
thousands of fragments, turned each

5
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:13,960
fragment into a long list of numbers,

6
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:16,800
and paid to store them in a special

7
00:00:13,960 --> 00:00:19,600
database. Then, this spring, one of the

8
00:00:16,800 --> 00:00:22,120
most respected names in AI looked at all

9
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:25,120
of it and said, "Just use a folder of

10
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:26,840
text files." And it worked better. Now,

11
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:29,160
Google's turned that folder into an

12
00:00:26,840 --> 00:00:31,480
official standard. Developers are

13
00:00:29,160 --> 00:00:33,840
calling it the most obvious idea they've

14
00:00:31,480 --> 00:00:35,000
ever seen, and they might be exactly

15
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:37,040
right.

16
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:40,360
The complicated version existed for a

17
00:00:37,040 --> 00:00:43,240
reason. Everything an AI needs to do its

18
00:00:40,360 --> 00:00:45,960
job is scattered. A metric's definition

19
00:00:43,240 --> 00:00:48,280
lives in one database. Its logic in some

20
00:00:45,960 --> 00:00:51,000
pipeline. The reason it changed in a

21
00:00:48,280 --> 00:00:53,040
6-month-old pull request. And the rest

22
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:55,520
in the head of an engineer who left in

23
00:00:53,040 --> 00:00:57,480
March. The standard fix was a thing

24
00:00:55,520 --> 00:01:00,640
called RAG. You take all those

25
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:02,800
documents, slice them into chunks, turn

26
00:01:00,640 --> 00:01:04,879
each chunk into a long list of numbers

27
00:01:02,800 --> 00:01:07,640
that captures [music] its rough meaning,

28
00:01:04,879 --> 00:01:10,000
and load them into a vector database.

29
00:01:07,640 --> 00:01:11,960
Ask a question, the system grabs the

30
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:14,520
chunks that look [music] closest to it,

31
00:01:11,960 --> 00:01:15,980
and hands them to the model. It works,

32
00:01:14,520 --> 00:01:16,280
but it never remembers.

33
00:01:15,980 --> 00:01:19,320
>> [music]

34
00:01:16,280 --> 00:01:21,720
>> Every query starts from zero. The model

35
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:23,760
gets a fresh pile of disconnected

36
00:01:21,720 --> 00:01:25,805
snippets and has to work out the same

37
00:01:23,760 --> 00:01:28,480
connections it worked out an hour

38
00:01:25,805 --> 00:01:30,080
[music] ago, and the hour before that.

39
00:01:28,480 --> 00:01:33,440
That respected name, by the way, was

40
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:35,631
Andrej Karpathy, co-founder of OpenAI,

41
00:01:33,440 --> 00:01:35,840
former head of AI at Tesla.

42
00:01:35,631 --> 00:01:38,040
>> [music]

43
00:01:35,840 --> 00:01:40,840
>> In April, he posted a short file to

44
00:01:38,040 --> 00:01:41,526
GitHub for an idea he called the LLM

45
00:01:40,840 --> 00:01:41,800
Wiki.

46
00:01:41,526 --> 00:01:44,400
>> [music]

47
00:01:41,800 --> 00:01:46,480
>> And it flips RAG on its head. Instead of

48
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:48,720
the model re-deriving everything the

49
00:01:46,480 --> 00:01:51,240
moment you ask, you build the knowledge

50
00:01:48,720 --> 00:01:53,600
up once [music] into a folder of plain

51
00:01:51,240 --> 00:01:56,360
text files that link to each other. A

52
00:01:53,600 --> 00:01:59,080
living encyclopedia the model can read

53
00:01:56,360 --> 00:02:01,180
the way a developer reads a code base.

54
00:01:59,080 --> 00:02:02,840
People hear a folder of notes and

55
00:02:01,180 --> 00:02:05,760
[music] assume they're the one writing

56
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:08,280
the notes. Wrong way around. You don't

57
00:02:05,760 --> 00:02:10,240
write [music] the wiki, the AI does. You

58
00:02:08,280 --> 00:02:12,840
bring it new material and ask good

59
00:02:10,240 --> 00:02:15,640
questions. It handles the summarizing,

60
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:18,400
the cross-referencing, the filing, all

61
00:02:15,640 --> 00:02:21,000
the upkeep nobody ever keeps up with.

62
00:02:18,400 --> 00:02:24,360
Karpathy's own line for it, Obsidian is

63
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,840
the IDE, the LLM is the programmer, the

64
00:02:24,360 --> 00:02:29,080
wiki is the code base. The folder is the

65
00:02:26,840 --> 00:02:31,640
part you own, the model is the worker

66
00:02:29,080 --> 00:02:34,440
who maintains it. This is where Google

67
00:02:31,640 --> 00:02:36,600
comes in. On June 12th, Google Cloud

68
00:02:34,440 --> 00:02:39,640
took that loose community idea and

69
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:42,080
published it as a formal spec, the Open

70
00:02:39,640 --> 00:02:45,240
Knowledge Format. The spec is almost

71
00:02:42,080 --> 00:02:48,160
comically small. A bundle is a folder.

72
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:50,840
Every file is one concept, a table, a

73
00:02:48,160 --> 00:02:53,600
metric, a playbook, whatever you've got.

74
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:56,160
The file's path is its name. Links

75
00:02:53,600 --> 00:02:58,840
between files form a graph. There are

76
00:02:56,160 --> 00:03:01,320
two special file names, one that lists

77
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:04,200
what's in a folder and one that logs

78
00:03:01,320 --> 00:03:07,160
changes. And there's exactly one hard

79
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:10,320
rule. Every file has to say what type of

80
00:03:07,160 --> 00:03:12,560
thing it is in one field. The spec also

81
00:03:10,320 --> 00:03:15,200
orders any tool reading a bundle to

82
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:17,480
forgive almost everything. Unknown

83
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:20,080
fields, broken links, even files it

84
00:03:17,480 --> 00:03:22,400
can't parse. An enterprise standard from

85
00:03:20,080 --> 00:03:23,707
Google whose defining feature is how

86
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:23,880
little it demands

87
00:03:23,707 --> 00:03:26,040
>> [music]

88
00:03:23,880 --> 00:03:28,360
>> and how much it lets you break. You

89
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:30,600
could build it in an afternoon. One

90
00:03:28,360 --> 00:03:32,880
thing Google dropped though, Karpathy's

91
00:03:30,600 --> 00:03:35,239
instructions for how the AI maintains

92
00:03:32,880 --> 00:03:37,720
the wiki. They kept the folder and left

93
00:03:35,239 --> 00:03:40,000
out the part that keeps it alive.

94
00:03:37,720 --> 00:03:42,640
Back to the reversal. The folder wins

95
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:44,560
and it wins for three reasons. First,

96
00:03:42,640 --> 00:03:47,239
when the work happens. RAG [music] does

97
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:49,800
its thinking at question time. The wiki

98
00:03:47,239 --> 00:03:51,840
does it once up front when the bundle is

99
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:54,160
built, connecting concepts, [music]

100
00:03:51,840 --> 00:03:56,960
flagging contradictions, writing the

101
00:03:54,160 --> 00:03:59,240
summaries. Pay that cost a single time,

102
00:03:56,960 --> 00:04:02,600
then just read the finished answer.

103
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:04,972
Second, skill. A model can only hold so

104
00:04:02,600 --> 00:04:06,880
much in its head at once, and a big

105
00:04:04,972 --> 00:04:09,680
[music] company has thousands of these

106
00:04:06,880 --> 00:04:10,867
files. Each folder carries a short table

107
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:10,880
of contents.

108
00:04:10,867 --> 00:04:12,800
>> [music]

109
00:04:10,880 --> 00:04:15,120
>> The model reads that first, picks the

110
00:04:12,800 --> 00:04:17,760
one file it needs, and skips the other

111
00:04:15,120 --> 00:04:21,000
9,000. It never chokes on the whole

112
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:23,680
library. Third, it's only text. It lives

113
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:26,120
in Git exactly like code. You can diff

114
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:27,720
it, review it in a pull request, [music]

115
00:04:26,120 --> 00:04:30,360
zip the whole thing and hand it to a

116
00:04:27,720 --> 00:04:32,360
model running offline on a laptop. You

117
00:04:30,360 --> 00:04:34,880
don't need a database, a server, or an

118
00:04:32,360 --> 00:04:37,760
API key to read it. If you can open a

119
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:40,640
file, you're good. Two quick mix-ups to

120
00:04:37,760 --> 00:04:43,040
clear up. This isn't competing with MCP.

121
00:04:40,640 --> 00:04:45,320
MCP is the pipe that moves data around

122
00:04:43,040 --> 00:04:47,960
live. This is the cargo that moves

123
00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:50,120
through it, and it's not an SEO trick.

124
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:52,520
Nothing in it helps a search engine find

125
00:04:50,120 --> 00:04:55,720
you. It's private knowledge for your own

126
00:04:52,520 --> 00:04:58,640
agents. The pitch is that the AI does

127
00:04:55,720 --> 00:05:00,640
the bookkeeping humans always abandon,

128
00:04:58,640 --> 00:05:02,960
but the spec has no mechanism to keep

129
00:05:00,640 --> 00:05:05,360
anything current. There's a field for a

130
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:08,000
timestamp, fine. A field is not a

131
00:05:05,360 --> 00:05:10,480
process. Nothing in the format updates

132
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:13,240
itself. This works beautifully when one

133
00:05:10,480 --> 00:05:15,919
person owns one folder. On a shared team

134
00:05:13,240 --> 00:05:18,320
folder, it goes stale in a month. Nobody

135
00:05:15,919 --> 00:05:20,200
volunteers to tend it, and the agent

136
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:22,560
starts answering from knowledge that

137
00:05:20,200 --> 00:05:24,880
expired back in spring. That's catch

138
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:27,360
one. Catch two is funnier. The whole

139
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:29,840
idea rests on AI being a tireless,

140
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:32,200
accurate librarian. In practice,

141
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:34,360
language models are bad at writing clean

142
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:37,160
markdown at scale. They botch the

143
00:05:34,360 --> 00:05:39,560
formatting, mangle headers, invent links

144
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:41,720
to files that were never created. And

145
00:05:39,560 --> 00:05:44,200
how did Google fix the messy librarian

146
00:05:41,720 --> 00:05:46,480
problem? They didn't. They changed the

147
00:05:44,200 --> 00:05:48,480
spec to order every reader to forgive

148
00:05:46,480 --> 00:05:51,080
the [music] mess. That permissive rule

149
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:53,000
is damage control with a nicer name. The

150
00:05:51,080 --> 00:05:55,680
deepest catch is the last [music] one.

151
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:58,280
The format standardizes the container,

152
00:05:55,680 --> 00:06:01,000
not the meaning. The one required field

153
00:05:58,280 --> 00:06:04,280
is a free-form label. Your team writes

154
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:06,800
BigQuery table. Mine writes table.

155
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:08,560
Someone else writes relational asset.

156
00:06:06,800 --> 00:06:10,400
They're all valid, but each is speaking

157
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:12,800
a different language. You can ship the

158
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:14,400
box anywhere. Agreeing on what's inside

159
00:06:12,800 --> 00:06:16,360
is still on you.

160
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:18,240
Strip all of this back and you land on a

161
00:06:16,360 --> 00:06:20,840
line some developer wrote that stuck

162
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:23,520
with me. An agent is basically just a

163
00:06:20,840 --> 00:06:25,840
folder of markdown files. Anyone can

164
00:06:23,520 --> 00:06:28,200
write markdown. The skill is in how the

165
00:06:25,840 --> 00:06:30,600
folder is organized. What's locked

166
00:06:28,200 --> 00:06:32,960
versus what the AI can rewrite. What

167
00:06:30,600 --> 00:06:35,640
stops it drifting over a long run. The

168
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:37,840
moat is invisible. Two folders can look

169
00:06:35,640 --> 00:06:40,320
identical. One holds up in production

170
00:06:37,840 --> 00:06:41,840
while the other slowly rots. You can't

171
00:06:40,320 --> 00:06:44,840
tell which is which by reading the

172
00:06:41,840 --> 00:06:46,440
files. No format can hand you that. Then

173
00:06:44,840 --> 00:06:49,360
there's the part Google would rather you

174
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:51,560
skim past. OKF didn't come out of

175
00:06:49,360 --> 00:06:54,600
Google's AI lab. It came from the

176
00:06:51,560 --> 00:06:57,200
BigQuery team. Every sample data set

177
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:59,880
ships on BigQuery. The reference tool

178
00:06:57,200 --> 00:07:01,960
that writes the bundles runs on Gemini.

179
00:06:59,880 --> 00:07:03,919
And the easiest place to pour a finished

180
00:07:01,960 --> 00:07:06,320
bundle is Google's own knowledge

181
00:07:03,919 --> 00:07:08,840
product. The one they just renamed for

182
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:10,600
exactly this moment. If you've seen our

183
00:07:08,840 --> 00:07:13,480
video on Gemma 4, I guess you can

184
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:16,280
already smell the strategy behind this.

185
00:07:13,480 --> 00:07:18,880
Will it stick? Hard to say. The day it

186
00:07:16,280 --> 00:07:21,000
launched, almost nobody outside Google

187
00:07:18,880 --> 00:07:23,919
was using it. And [music] a standard

188
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:26,520
with one user is just a suggestion. It

189
00:07:23,919 --> 00:07:29,040
could easily be the next Google project

190
00:07:26,520 --> 00:07:31,600
added to their graveyard. The idea

191
00:07:29,040 --> 00:07:33,440
underneath it has already won though.

192
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:35,760
The most overfunded field [music] in

193
00:07:33,440 --> 00:07:37,880
tech spent two years and a fortune

194
00:07:35,760 --> 00:07:41,080
convincing itself that giving a machine

195
00:07:37,880 --> 00:07:43,880
memory needed exotic infrastructure.

196
00:07:41,080 --> 00:07:46,160
Then a tidy folder of text files did the

197
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:49,080
job better. Whatever happens to the

198
00:07:46,160 --> 00:07:51,760
format, that part isn't going back in

199
00:07:49,080 --> 00:07:51,760
the box.
